<HEADLINE>
<P>
GLENDALE / BURBANK FOCUS: GLENDALE; POLICE TO HOLD FREE ANTI-CRIME EXPO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What can you do to protect yourself from crime? 
</P>
<P>
 The Glendale Police Department plans to answer this and related questions at a 
free Crime Prevention Expo, 10 a.m. to 2 p.m. Saturday at City Hall.In addition 
to police, representatives from about 15 local stores that sell home security 
and other anti-crime merchandise will attend, and there will be demonstrations 
on self-protection. 
</P>
<P>
 "The purpose of this is to let the public know we're available to help them in 
such ways as coming to the community to talk about forming Neighborhood Watch 
groups, or inspecting residences for security," said Kathy Allen, a community 
service officer. 
</P>
<P>
 Held in connection with California Crime Prevention Month and the first of its 
kind in the city, the expo will also provide answers to some of the most 
frequently asked security questions, Allen said. Those questions include how to 
secure sliding and double-hung windows against intruders. 
</P>
<P>
 Businesses scheduled to be on hand for the event include private security 
companies, home security and car alarm dealers and a cellular phone company.  
</P>
<P>
 Students from the International Karate Assn. of Glendale will demonstrate 
self-defense techniques, organizers said. STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</TEXT>
