COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: LAGUNA NIGUEL; 8.4 ACRES DONATED FOR NEW CITY PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council this week agreed to accept a developer's 8.4-acre donation 
for use as the city's latest public park, Clipper Cove Park.  
</P>
<P>
 The park will have 3.5 acres for two playgrounds, picnic tables, a garden 
area, fitness stations and two turf areas not intended for use in organized 
sports.The park will be located between Thackeray Drive, Clipper Way and 
Kensington Drive and will be surrounded by almost five acres of landscaped 
slopes. 
</P>
<P>
 The agreement caps years of negotiations over the proposed park site. The 
delay stemmed partly from an argument between the developer, Shapell Industries 
and the city over who would maintain the slopes around the park. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the agreement, the city will maintain 1.4 acres of slopes created when 
the land is graded and the local homeowners association will maintain the rest. 
LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
