<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Four devoutly religious women lived across the street from a bordello. They 
would watch the front door of the bordello and remark about everyone entering 
and leaving. As they looked one night, the first person to emerge was the 
pastor of a church the women didn't attend. "Isn't that shameful? A man of the 
cloth," said one woman. "I always said that people who went to that church were 
bums." 
</P>
<P>
 A few minutes later, they watched as their own pastor left. At first quiet, 
the woman spoke up again: "There must be someone real sick in there." 
</P>
<P>
 -- Ralph Zaldin, Laguna Hills * 
</P>
<P>
 While sitting in a bus waiting room, reader Susie Stock of Tarzana noticed 
that her 2 1/2-year-old daughter had begun peeling the paper off her new 
crayons. When her mom asked why she was doing that, the little girl replied: 
</P>
<P>
 "They are happier when they're naked."  
</P>
